4bc1a997-f980-48e6-9979-37d5d93429f0.902bfb88-4ca2-40da-9b94-0946b89f61a2.description=
This operation reads the content of a file. The operation can be used to read the entire file content in one step or to iterate the file line by line.

Inputs\:
    source - The full path and filename of the file to be read. A UNC path can be supported as the source file path.
    filter - The string to filter on (leave blank for no filter). If this filter is not blank, all rows that contain the filter string will be returned. If no match is found, no lines will be returned.
    iterate - Determines whether the content of the file should be iterated or not. If set to "true", the content of the file will be iterated row by row and for each subsequent call, the next row will be returned. If set to "false", the content of the file will not be iterated and only the number of lines that matched the "filter" will be returned.
Valid values\: true, false
    delimiter – If specified, the entire content of the file  will be read, the specified value will be used as a delimiter between the rows and  the resulting content will be returned. If left blank, the next row will be returned for each subsequent call. 
    eofReset - If set to true, after the No More response has been returned once, the operation will restart reading the file from the beginning on the next call.
Valid values\: true, false
    characterSet - The character set of the file to read from. For invalid or empty input value the default encoding will be used. 
Valid values\: UTF-8, UTF-16 and UTF-32 
Default value\: UTF-8

Results\:
    returnCode - This is the primary output. It is 0 if the operation completed successfully  (or if more rows are available when iterate is set to true), 1 if no more items (if iterate is set to true) and -1 in case of failure. 
    count - The number of lines that matched the filter, or if no filter specified, the total lines read (if iterate is false, or delimiter is not null). Otherwise, it returns the number of rows available for retrieval from the source file.
    returnResult - Each row by turn (if iterate is true and delimiter is blank) or all rows separated by the delimiter (if iterate is true and delimiter is not blank).
    exception - An exception message if the operation fails.

Responses\:
    success - The operation successfully read the file (if iterate is true, more rows are available).
    no more items - No more items are available for retrieval (if iterate is set to true).
    failure - The operation failed to read the file.

Notes\:
1. The "filter" and "eofReset" fields are taken into consideration only if iterate is set to true. Otherwise, they have no impact on the result.
2. Note that the "filter" match is not performed based on a regular expression, although the filter field may contain one. The operation only checks for each row if it contains the string given as filter. 
3. If i"terate" is set to "true" and "delimiter" is not null, the entire file may or may not still be fully read at once, depending on size. 
4. If "iterate" is set to "true", then all matching lines are pushed into the Session and then, subsequent calls to the operation, result in the next line being returned.
5. If the value provided in the "delimiter" field is not null, the entire file will be read once and returned regardless of the value of the "iterate" field.

Examples\:
    The following examples are used to illustrate the behavior of the operation for three specific use cases. For these examples, the operation will use as the input source a file called "example.txt", with the absolute path "C\:\Program Files\example.txt" and the following content\:
        "line1
         line2
         line3
         line4"
1. This is a valid inputs example for reading the content of a file, when the "iterate" input field is set to "true" and the "delimiter" input field is not left blank\:
        source\: C\:\Program Files\example.txt
        filter\:
        iterate\: true
        delimiter\: ,
        eofReset\: false
        characterSet\: UTF-8
    In this case, the "returnResult" output field of the operation will have the following value\: line1,line2,line3,line4
2. This is a valid inputs example for reading the content of a file, when the "iterate" input field is set to "true" and the delimiter input field is left blank\:
        source\: C\:\Program Files\example.txt
        filter\:
        iterate\: true
        delimiter\:
        eofReset\: false
        characterSet\: UTF-8
    In this case, the file will be iterated row by row in four subsequent calls. At each call, the "returnResult" output field of the operation will contain the value of one line from the file, in the same order as they are found in the source file (i.e. line1, line2, lin3, line4). 
3. This is a valid inputs example for reading the content of a file, when the "iterate" input field is set to "false" and the "delimiter" input field is left blank\:       
        source\: C\:\Program Files\example.txt
        filter\:
        iterate\: false
        delimiter\:
        eofReset\: false
        characterSet\: UTF-8
    In this case, the "returnResult" output field of the operation will be blank and the count output field will contain the value 4 (representing the number of lines in the file).
4bc1a997-f980-48e6-9979-37d5d93429f0.aa8e41e4-551d-42b6-b702-980cdd2daa5b.description=
This operation waits for the number of seconds specified in the "seconds" input.

Inputs\:
    seconds - The number of seconds to wait.

Results\:
    resultString – This is the primary output. It contains the "completed sleep" message if the operation completed successfully and an error message otherwise. 

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.
4bc1a997-f980-48e6-9979-37d5d93429f0.c548aaf1-9dab-4d3d-a7c7-6766a50331a7.description=
Runs multiple Shell commands by creating a SSH shell and checking output against regular expressions.

Inputs\:
    host - The hostname/IP address of the target machine.
    port - The port number for SSH protocol.
Default value\: 22
    username - Name of the account on the target machine.
    password - The password for the username. When using a private key file or a private key string, this input will be used as the passphrase for the file or string. For security reasons it is recommend to provide this input and protect the private key when using the 'privateKeyData' and the 'privateKeyFile' inputs.
    proxyHost - The proxy server used to access the remote machine.
    proxyPort - The proxy server port. Default\: 8080. Valid values\: -1 and numbers greater than 0.
    proxyUsername - The user name used when connecting to the proxy.
    proxyPassword - The proxy server password associated with the proxyUsername input value.
    privateKeyFile - Path to private key file (OpenSSH type) on the machine where is the worker. For security reasons it is recommend that the private key be protected by a passphrase that should be provided through the 'password' input.
    privateKeyData – A string representing the private key (OpenSSH type) used for authenticating the user. This string is usually the content of a private key file. The 'privateKeyData' and the 'privateKeyFile' inputs are mutually exclusive. For security reasons it is recommend that the private key be protected by a passphrase that should be provided through the 'password' input.
    knownHostsPolicy - The policy used for managing known_hosts file. We recommend to use a "strict" policy so as to verify the host key against a local file containing known, trustworthy machines. If you choose "allow" or "add" policy then you will connect to the server without any verification. If there is a Man-In-The-Middle attack then you will be connected to a fake server and the SSH commands that you send will go through that fake server. 
Valid values\:  
allow\=It will permit the connection to any hosts. 
strict\=It will permit the connection only to the hosts specified in known_hosts file. 
add\=It will permit the connection to any hosts, if the host is not in the known_hosts file it will be added. 
Default value\: strict
    allowedCiphers - A comma separated list of ciphers that will be used in the client-server handshake mechanism when the connection is created. Check the notes section for security concerns regarding your choice of ciphers. The default value will be used even if the input is not added to the operation.
Default value\: aes128-ctr,aes128-cbc,3des-ctr,3des-cbc,blowfish-cbc,aes192-ctr,aes192-cbc,aes256-ctr,aes256-cbc
    command - The commands to execute. This should be made up of 'send ' and 'expect ' statements separated by newlineCharacters.
    characterSet - The characterSet name for input stream encoding from the target machine.
Examples\: SJIS, EUC-JP, UTF-8
Default value\: UTF-8
    newlineCharacters - The character sequence to send as the enter key being pressed after each 'send' statement as the send expect script is processed in the command input. Either '\r\n' '\n' '\r' or a comma delimited list of ASCII escape sequences.
    timeout - Time in milliseconds to wait for the command to complete.
Default value\: 90000
    connectTimeout - Time in milliseconds to wait for the connection to be made.
Default value\: 10000
    sessionId - Identifier of a shared SSH shell session created by SSH Shell Logon. Instead of creating a new SSH shell session this one will be used if specified.

Results\:
    returnResult - The primary output.
    STDOUT - The standard output of the command(s).
    visualized - The output of the command in XML format.
    TimedOut - Is set to "true" if the value set in the "timeout" input has elapsed and the command timed out.

Responses\:
    success - The operation was executed successfully.
    failure - The connection could not be established or the commands are invalid for this operation (not for target machine's shell).

Notes\:
1. The following commands are supported\:
1.1. Send a Shell command.
    send 
Examples\: send ls
1.2. Send a char given by ASCII code.
    sendChar 
Examples\: sendChar 32
1.3. Match the entire previous command output against the regex.
    expect 
Examples\: expect (.*?)Desktop(.*)
1.4. The entire previous command output ends with the given text.
    expectEndsWith 
1.5. Match the last line from the previous command output against the regex.
    expectLastLine 
1.6. Fail on the success of the expect command\: expect, expectEndsWith or expectLastLine.
    errorOn 
1.7. If the expect command is successful then the operation will always execute the send command.
    always 
    on 
Examples\: 
Single line output\: always sendChar 121
                           on expect (.*?)Press y to continue(.*)
Multiple line output example 1\: always sendChar 121
                             	 on expect (?s)(.*?)Press y to continue(.*)
Multiple line output example 2\: always sendChar 121
                             	 on expectLastLine (.*?)Press y to continue(.*)
1.8. Use a different timeout for this send command\: send, sendChar.
    wait  
1.9. Use a different timeout for this expect command\: expect, expectEndsWith or expectLastLine.
    wait  
2. Hidden inputs\:
    knownHostsPath -  Specifies the path to the known_hots file on the running server.
Default value\: /.ssh/known_hosts
Examples\: /home/admin/.ssh/known_hosts
    readTimeout - Time in milliseconds to wait for reading and then matching the output with the regex from expect command.
Default value\: 20000
3. In order to use private keys with different encryption types (ex.\: aes256-cbc) needs to be updated the /java/lib/security/local_policy.jar JAR file with one that accept all security policies (ex.\: http\://www.oracle.com/technetwork/java/javase/downloads/jce-7-download-432124.html). After update you must restart the Studio or Central service.
4. The operation supports connections through HTTP proxy with username and password authentication.
5. For security reasons, HPE does not recommend the use of outdated or vulnerable ciphers. Therefore "arcfour" cihpers should be avoided because they do not provide confidentiality for data in transit and using them can lead to information leakage.
Arcfour is vulnerable to the following attacks\: Fluhrer, Mantin and Shamir attack, Klein's attack, Royal Holloway attack, Bar-mitzvah attack and NOMORE attack.

4bc1a997-f980-48e6-9979-37d5d93429f0.f73438b0-2daa-4e44-8399-c369ecbc436a.description=
This operation runs a command, allowing you to specify whether it runs locally (no port to be specified), via SSH, Global Shell, ROSH, Telnet, or RSH.

Inputs\:
    host - The host name or IP address.
    port - The port number used to connect to the host.
    username - The user name used to connect.
    password - The password associated with the "username" input. If using a private key file, this is the passphrase for the file.
    protocol - The protocol used to run the command. 
Valid values\: SSH, ROSH, GlobalShell, Telnet, RSH, REXEC, local, WMI, NASConnectTelnet, HPOM
    timeout - The time to wait for the command to complete (in milliseconds). Increase this value if you are getting incomplete output results or a timeout.
Default value\: 90000 (90 seconds), 600000 (if protocol->WMI)
    command - The command to run.
    arguments - The arguments to pass to the command.
    environment - Specifies the environment variables and values that need to be defined when running the command.
    startDir - The path to the starting directory.
    pty - Specifies whether to use pty (used by SSH, GlobalShell)
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: false
    privateKeyFile - The absolute path to the private key file on the RAS host (used by SSH, GlobalShell).
    sasHost - The host on which to run the ROSH command.
    sasHostUsername - The user name used to run the ROSH command on "sasHost".
    usernamePrompt - The prompt message for the user name. Used by the Telnet protocol. 
Default value\: When used by the NASConnectTelnet protocol, the default value is "NAS Login\:".
    passwordPrompt - The prompt message for the password associated with the "usernamePrompt"  input. Used by the Telnet protocol.  
Default value\: When used by the 'NASConnectTelnet' protocol, the default value is "Password\:"
    outputPath - The network accessible path where to store the temporary files. If you do not specify this input, it points to '\\host\admin$\temp\'. If this path is not accessible, change it to use another share to which the host local system account has write access. By default, the path needs to be changed on Windows 2000 systems.
    nasDevice - The NAS device on which to run the command when using the 'NASConnect' protocol.
    nasDeviceConsoleMode - The NAS device console mode used to run the command scripts running the command on the specified NAS device. If you leave this input empty, command scripts are not used, and the connections to the NAS device and the command are issued directly in the console. This is not recommended. Due to error handling capabilities limitation, the result might be a success even if the command failed to run. You can find the values for this input in the NAS web interface, as a drop-down list when creating a new command script (for example, Cisco IOS enable).
    hpomNode - The node on which to run the command.
    hpomProtocol - The protocol used to communicate with HPOM 
Valid values\: HTTP or HTTPS.
    characterSet - The name of the character set used for stream encoding and decoding between the RAS and target machine.
Valid values\: SJIS,EUC-JP, UTF-8
Default value\: UTF-8 (used by SSH, GlobalShell, Telnet, RSH, REXEC)

Hidden Inputs\:
    useDelegation - This input only applies to the WMI protocol. If set to "true" the operation will use the 'Delegate' impersonation level and the 'Kerberos' authentication protocol. If 'false', empty or missing the operation will use 'Impersonate' for the impersonation level and the default authentication protocol (which is NTLM).
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: false

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. Used to determine the operation response, specifying whether the operation is successful or not.
    stdOut - The standard output (STDOUT) of the command.
    stdErr - The standard error (STDERR) of the command.

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

Notes\:
Telnet protocol - Since telnet is a shell protocol, not a remote execution protocol, the response is always  successful if the command is ran in the remote shell.  The return code of the specified command cannot be determined in this protocol.  If you must use the telnet protocol with this operation, make sure to check the command results. Consider using the SSH or REXEC protocol instead.
